#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:165
msgid "What just happened under the hood?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:167
msgid ""
"Scrapy sends the first :class:`scrapy.Request <scrapy.Request>` objects "
"yielded by the :meth:`~scrapy.Spider.start` spider method. Upon receiving a "
"response for each one, Scrapy calls the callback method associated with the "
"request (in this case, the ``parse`` method) with a :class:`~scrapy.http."
"Response` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:175
msgid "A shortcut to the ``start`` method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:177
msgid ""
"Instead of implementing a :meth:`~scrapy.Spider.start` method that yields :"
"class:`~scrapy.Request` objects from URLs, you can define a :attr:`~scrapy."
"Spider.start_urls` class attribute with a list of URLs. This list will then "
"be used by the default implementation of :meth:`~scrapy.Spider.start` to "
"create the initial requests for your spider."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:184
msgid ""
"from pathlib import Path\n"
"\n"
"import scrapy\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class QuotesSpider(scrapy.Spider):\n"
"    name = \"quotes\"\n"
"    start_urls = [\n"
"        \"https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/1/\",\n"
"        \"https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/2/\",\n"
"    ]\n"
"\n"
"    def parse(self, response):\n"
"        page = response.url.split(\"/\")[-2]\n"
"        filename = f\"quotes-{page}.html\"\n"
"        Path(filename).write_bytes(response.body)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../intro/tutorial.rst:203
msgid ""
"The :meth:`~scrapy.Spider.parse` method will be called to handle each of the "
"requests for those URLs, even though we haven't explicitly told Scrapy to do "
"so. This happens because :meth:`~scrapy.Spider.parse` is Scrapy's default "
"callback method, which is called for requests without an explicitly assigned "
"callback."
msgstr ""

